GROUP BY is used to group rows that have the same values in a column.


You have a table orders:

 customer	   price
| Ali	    |    100 |
| Sara    |  	200  |
| Ali	    |     50 |


SELECT customer, SUM(price)
FROM orders
GROUP BY customer;

customer	SUM(price)
Ali	       150
Sara	     200

So we grouped by customer and calculated total price for each one.

What is HAVING:
HAVING is used to filter groups AFTER grouping.
GROUP BY → makes groups
HAVING → filters those groups


SELECT customer, SUM(price) AS total
FROM orders
GROUP BY customer
HAVING total > 160;

customer	total
Sara	     200


Difference between WHERE and HAVING

          WHERE	                                         HAVING
|  Filters rows BEFORE grouping	             |  Filters groups AFTER grouping |
|  Cannot use SUM(), COUNT()...	             |  Can use SUM(), COUNT()...     |
|  Used without GROUP BY or before it        | 	Used with GROUP BY            |


using weher 
SELECT customer, price
FROM orders
WHERE price > 100;


using having SELECT customer, SUM(price)
FROM orders
GROUP BY customer
HAVING SUM(price) > 100;


Easy Rule (remember this):
WHERE → before grouping
GROUP BY → make groups
HAVING → after grouping


